1
00:00:00,100 --> 00:00:03,293
We shipped six features before lunch today.

2
00:00:03,293 --> 00:00:03,590
Six.

3
00:00:03,590 --> 00:00:04,778
Not a hackathon.

4
00:00:04,778 --> 00:00:05,521
A Tuesday.

5
00:00:05,521 --> 00:00:10,422
And I almost spent that morning planning how to ship them instead.

6
00:00:10,422 --> 00:00:15,769
Writing a phase document, sequencing dependencies, estimating timelines.

7
00:00:15,769 --> 00:00:17,477
Then I just built them.

8
00:00:17,477 --> 00:00:22,898
Health checks, retry logic, progress hooks, a babysitter, a phase runner.

9
00:00:22,898 --> 00:00:24,755
Each one: twenty minutes.

10
00:00:24,755 --> 00:00:28,839
The planning would have taken longer than the building.

11
00:00:28,839 --> 00:00:30,398
That's the inversion.

12
00:00:30,398 --> 00:00:31,809
Jake's Daily Build.

13
00:00:31,809 --> 00:00:32,849
What we built.

14
00:00:32,849 --> 00:00:33,666
What broke.

15
00:00:33,666 --> 00:00:34,780
What I learned.

16
00:00:34,780 --> 00:00:38,864
Two recent talks by Nate B Jones nail what's happening.

17
00:00:38,864 --> 00:00:42,355
For decades, execution was the expensive thing.

18
00:00:42,355 --> 00:00:43,988
Engineers were scarce.

19
00:00:43,988 --> 00:00:45,474
Training took years.

20
00:00:45,474 --> 00:00:47,256
Every hour was precious.

21
00:00:47,256 --> 00:00:50,598
So we built rituals to protect that capacity.

22
00:00:50,598 --> 00:00:51,934
Planning meetings.

23
00:00:51,934 --> 00:00:53,048
Approval gates.

24
00:00:53,048 --> 00:00:53,420
PRDs.

25
00:00:53,420 --> 00:00:59,361
All designed to prevent wasting expensive engineering time on the wrong problem.

26
00:00:59,361 --> 00:01:00,549
That made sense.

27
00:01:00,549 --> 00:01:05,079
When the meeting costs less than the build, hold the meeting.

28
00:01:05,079 --> 00:01:08,346
When rework is expensive, plan meticulously.

29
00:01:08,346 --> 00:01:10,054
AI inverted that ratio.

30
00:01:10,054 --> 00:01:13,619
The meeting now takes longer than the prototype.

31
00:01:13,619 --> 00:01:19,263
One major AI lab shipped a full product feature in 10 days with four people.

32
00:01:19,263 --> 00:01:22,456
I've seen PRD cycles take longer than that.

33
00:01:22,456 --> 00:01:24,833
The bottleneck didn't disappear.

34
00:01:24,833 --> 00:01:26,615
It moved to four things.

35
00:01:26,615 --> 00:01:27,209
Clarity.

36
00:01:27,209 --> 00:01:29,734
Do you know what's worth building?

37
00:01:29,734 --> 00:01:33,001
You can build faster than you can think now.

38
00:01:33,001 --> 00:01:33,670
Ambition.

39
00:01:33,670 --> 00:01:37,457
When shipping is cheap, small bets become timidity.

40
00:01:37,457 --> 00:01:39,908
50 swings a year instead of four.

41
00:01:39,908 --> 00:01:42,284
The danger isn't building wrong.

42
00:01:42,284 --> 00:01:44,512
It's not swinging hard enough.

43
00:01:44,512 --> 00:01:45,477
Distribution.

44
00:01:45,477 --> 00:01:47,260
Everybody can build now.

45
00:01:47,260 --> 00:01:48,968
Product isn't the moat.

46
00:01:48,968 --> 00:01:50,824
Getting it into hands is.

47
00:01:50,824 --> 00:01:58,399
One AI company partnered with a 300,000-person services firm instead of building their own sales team.

48
00:01:58,399 --> 00:02:00,404
Distribution beats product.

49
00:02:00,404 --> 00:02:01,444
Relationships.

50
00:02:01,444 --> 00:02:04,043
You can't vibe-code a relationship.

51
00:02:04,043 --> 00:02:09,093
When technical skills become commodity, trust is the differentiator.

52
00:02:09,093 --> 00:02:12,954
The second talk introduces a split most people miss.

53
00:02:12,954 --> 00:02:17,039
Disposable software is two completely different things.

54
00:02:17,039 --> 00:02:20,306
One: throwaway tools for throwaway problems.

55
00:02:20,306 --> 00:02:22,237
A dashboard you need once.

56
00:02:22,237 --> 00:02:23,351
Genuinely good.

57
00:02:23,351 --> 00:02:24,985
Democratizes software.

58
00:02:24,985 --> 00:02:28,401
Two: disposable features inside real products.

59
00:02:28,401 --> 00:02:32,263
Ship a hundred, see what sticks, harden the winners.

60
00:02:32,263 --> 00:02:35,901
One major code editor ships multiple times a day.

61
00:02:35,901 --> 00:02:41,545
When users complain about instability, the answer is: this pace is required.

62
00:02:41,545 --> 00:02:44,961
That works when your customers are developers.

63
00:02:44,961 --> 00:02:47,338
Developers tolerate instability.

64
00:02:47,338 --> 00:02:49,566
They'll fix things themselves.

65
00:02:49,566 --> 00:02:52,016
That's 5% of the software market.

66
00:02:52,016 --> 00:02:54,244
The other 95% buy reliability.

67
00:02:54,244 --> 00:02:59,145
Enterprise customers buy something they don't have to think about.

68
00:02:59,145 --> 00:03:01,076
Tuesday works like Monday.

69
00:03:01,076 --> 00:03:03,824
Next quarter looks like this quarter.

70
00:03:03,824 --> 00:03:07,834
Disposable software is the opposite of what they need.

71
00:03:07,834 --> 00:03:11,473
The winning enterprise strategy isn't disposable.

72
00:03:11,473 --> 00:03:13,478
It's proactive reliability.

73
00:03:13,478 --> 00:03:18,157
Earn trust through boring uptime, security, responsive support.

74
00:03:18,157 --> 00:03:22,390
Then extend that trust into agents that anticipate needs.

75
00:03:22,390 --> 00:03:24,989
Not chatbots that wait to be asked.

76
00:03:24,989 --> 00:03:29,370
Agents that surface insights before you know you need them.

77
00:03:29,370 --> 00:03:31,598
Five things this means for us.

78
00:03:31,598 --> 00:03:31,895
One.

79
00:03:31,895 --> 00:03:35,311
We're in the right game with the right habits.

80
00:03:35,311 --> 00:03:38,133
Build first, plan light, iterate fast.

81
00:03:38,133 --> 00:03:42,143
Our plan files are one-page checklists, not documents.

82
00:03:42,143 --> 00:03:46,896
Our knowledge graph surfaces what needs attention before we ask.

83
00:03:46,896 --> 00:03:49,050
That's the proactive pattern.

84
00:03:49,050 --> 00:03:49,347
Two.

85
00:03:49,347 --> 00:03:51,872
We're playing two different games.

86
00:03:51,872 --> 00:03:54,842
Our agent runtime is developer software.

87
00:03:54,842 --> 00:03:57,070
Ship fast, iterate constantly.

88
00:03:57,070 --> 00:03:59,966
Our messaging app is consumer software.

89
00:03:59,966 --> 00:04:01,674
Users want reliability.

90
00:04:01,674 --> 00:04:03,085
Different playbook.

91
00:04:03,085 --> 00:04:03,531
Three.

92
00:04:03,531 --> 00:04:04,422
The big one.

93
00:04:04,422 --> 00:04:06,724
We have a distribution problem.

94
00:04:06,724 --> 00:04:12,071
We keep building features instead of getting things into people's hands.

95
00:04:12,071 --> 00:04:13,408
The runtime works.

96
00:04:13,408 --> 00:04:14,819
Repo still private.

97
00:04:14,819 --> 00:04:19,349
The messaging app has a landing page with a placeholder form.

98
00:04:19,349 --> 00:04:24,324
We're optimizing for execution when execution isn't the bottleneck.

99
00:04:24,324 --> 00:04:24,695
Four.

100
00:04:24,695 --> 00:04:27,146
Attention is the real constraint.

101
00:04:27,146 --> 00:04:29,374
Every hour on internal tooling

102
00:04:29,374 --> 00:04:33,384
doesn't face customers is an hour not on distribution.

103
00:04:33,384 --> 00:04:36,280
Vibe-coding your own tools sounds free.

104
00:04:36,280 --> 00:04:38,137
The attention cost isn't.

105
00:04:38,137 --> 00:04:38,508
Five.

106
00:04:38,508 --> 00:04:41,850
The proactive AI angle is our differentiator.

107
00:04:41,850 --> 00:04:45,192
The knowledge graph doesn't wait to be asked.

108
00:04:45,192 --> 00:04:50,390
It scores health, surfaces priorities, detects patterns across commits

109
00:04:50,390 --> 00:04:51,430
conversations.

110
00:04:51,430 --> 00:04:57,297
That's exactly the proactive agent the enterprise talk describes as the future.

111
00:04:57,297 --> 00:05:04,871
Not "we built a knowledge graph." Position it as: the system anticipates what you need before you ask.

112
00:05:04,871 --> 00:05:06,208
Actions this week.

113
00:05:06,208 --> 00:05:08,584
Flip the runtime repo to public.

114
00:05:08,584 --> 00:05:11,926
Replace the placeholder form with a real one.

115
00:05:11,926 --> 00:05:15,936
Track the ratio of building time to distribution time.

116
00:05:15,936 --> 00:05:21,729
If it's 90-10, and it probably is, we're still protecting execution in a world

117
00:05:21,729 --> 00:05:23,437
execution isn't scarce.

118
00:05:23,437 --> 00:05:24,922
Two things to build.

119
00:05:24,922 --> 00:05:27,298
First: a distribution scorecard.

120
00:05:27,298 --> 00:05:30,714
Hours building versus hours shipping to users.

121
00:05:30,714 --> 00:05:31,680
Track weekly.

122
00:05:31,680 --> 00:05:36,878
If it stays above 80-20 for two weeks, something's structurally wrong.

123
00:05:36,878 --> 00:05:39,477
Second: a proactive insight digest.

124
00:05:39,477 --> 00:05:41,705
Weekly auto-generated summary.

125
00:05:41,705 --> 00:05:44,973
What the system learned, fixed, and flagged.

126
00:05:44,973 --> 00:05:47,721
Written for a non-technical audience.

127
00:05:47,721 --> 00:05:50,023
Dogfood the proactive AI pitch.

128
00:05:50,023 --> 00:05:55,444
If we can't make it compelling for ourselves, we can't sell it to anyone.

129
00:05:55,444 --> 00:05:57,523
That's The Bottleneck Moved.

130
00:05:57,523 --> 00:05:58,191
I'm Jake.

131
00:05:58,191 --> 00:05:59,900
Catch you next episode.
